ECLOGUE IV.

A singing match between two unfriendly shepherds, on the model of Virgil's third Eclogue, or Calpurnius’ sixth. They sing of the birth of Charles VIII, and of his glorious reign. The approximate date of the poem is suggested by the reference to the King’s recent marriage (Dee. 6, 1491).
